'''Manuel Obafemi Akanji''' {{Audio|Manuel_Obafemi_Akanji.wav|listen}} ({{IPA|de-CH|ˈmaː.nu.ɛl aˈkan.dʒi}}; born 19 July 1995) is a Swiss professional [[Association football|footballer]] who plays as a [[Defender (association football)|defender]] for {{Italian football updater|Internazionale}} club [[Inter Milan]], on loan from {{English football updater|ManchesC}} club [[Manchester City F.C.|Manchester City]], and the [[Switzerland national football team|Switzerland national team]].

An academy graduate of [[FC Winterthur]], Akanji's professional career began in 2014, when he made his debut for the then-[[Swiss Challenge League]] club, having also previously played for the club's second team. He moved to [[Swiss Super League|first tier]] [[FC Basel]] in 2015, where he won consecutive league titles in [[2015–16 FC Basel season|2015–16]] and [[2016–17 FC Basel season|2016–17]], the latter of which was a double that included the [[2016–17 Swiss Cup]]. Following his success with Basel, Akanji was sold to [[Borussia Dortmund]] during the winter transfer window of 2018. During his stay in the [[Bundesliga]], he helped Dortmund win the [[2019 DFL-Supercup]] and the [[2020–21 DFB-Pokal]]. He joined Manchester City in 2022, winning a [[Treble (association football)#Continental trebles|continental treble]] in his [[2022–23 Manchester City F.C. season|first season]] with the club, as well as numerous other trophies, including one more Premier League title in [[2023–24 Premier League|2023–24]].

Internationally, Akanji represents Switzerland, making his debut for the senior team in 2017 after featuring for the [[Switzerland national under-20 football team|under-20]] and [[Switzerland national under-21 football team|under-21]] sides. He was a member of Switzerland's squad for two editions of the [[UEFA European Championship]], in [[UEFA Euro 2020|2020]] and [[UEFA Euro 2024|2024]], as well as two [[FIFA World Cup]]s, in [[2018 FIFA World Cup|2018]] and [[2022 FIFA World Cup|2022]].

==Club career==
===Youth football and early career===
Akanji began his youth career with the local club in [[Wiesendangen]]. In May 2007, Akanji changed clubs and was a youth-team player for [[FC Winterthur]], featuring for their under-18 team and later with their second team. In the [[2014–15 Swiss Challenge League|2014–15 Challenge League]], he became a regular starter for Winterthur, having played two games for them during the second half of the previous season.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://fcwinterthur.ch/news/2022-09/der-fc-winterthur-gratuliert-manuel-akanji-zum-transfer-von-dortmund-zu-manchester-city |title=Der FC Winterthur gratuliert Manuel Akanji zum Transfer von Dortmund zu Manchester City! |publisher=FC Winterthur |language=German |date=2 September 2022 |accessdate=28 August 2024|trans-title=FC Winterthur congratulates Manuel Akanji on his transfer from Dortmund to Manchester City!}}</ref>

===FC Basel===
On 15 April 2015, it was announced that Akanji would be transferred to [[FC Basel]] for the [[2015–16 Swiss Super League|2015–16 Swiss Super League season]].<ref name="TW">{{Cite news |last=Waldis |first=Samuel |title=Ein neuer Verteidiger für den FCB: Manuel Akanji kommt vom FC Winterthur |trans-title=A new defender for FCB: Manuel Akanji comes from FC Winterthur |url=http://www.tageswoche.ch/de/2015_16/sport/685528/ |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160131165554/http://www.tageswoche.ch/de/2015_16/sport/685528/ |archive-date=2016-01-31 |access-date=2026-03-14 |work=Tageswoche |language=en}}</ref> He made his [[Swiss Super League]] debut on 26 September 2015 being substituted in against [[FC Lugano]]. Under manager [[Urs Fischer (footballer)|Urs Fischer]], Akanji won the [[Swiss Super League]] championship at the end of the [[2015–16 Swiss Super League|2015–16 Super League season]].<ref name="fcb 2016-04-30">{{cite web |first=Casper |last=Marti |year=2016 |url=http://www.fcb.ch/de-CH/News/2016/04/30/FCB-Sion |title=Es ist vollbracht ! Der FCB ist zum 19. Mal Meister |publisher=FC Basel |accessdate=30 April 2016|trans-title=It is done! FCB are champions for the 19th time.}}</ref> Basel then won the [[2016–17 Swiss Super League]] and [[2016–17 Swiss Cup]] double, making it the sixth time the club had achieved this feat in its history.<ref name="fcb 2017-06-02">{{cite web |first=Casper |last=Marti |year=2017 |url=https://www.fcb.ch/de-CH/News/2017/06/02/Der-Saisonabschluss-im-Zeitraffer |title=Der Saisonabschluss im Zeitraffer |publisher=FC Basel |accessdate=2 June 2017 |archive-date=6 June 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170606014425/https://www.fcb.ch/de-CH/News/2017/06/02/Der-Saisonabschluss-im-Zeitraffer |url-status=dead }}</ref>

As Swiss Champions, Basel qualified for the [[2017–18 UEFA Champions League]] and started in the [[2017–18 UEFA Champions League group stage|group stage]]. Akanji played the full 90 minutes in all six games and helped the team finish second in its group, thus qualifying for the knockout phase.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.fcb.ch/aktuell/news/1-mannschaft/2017/12/amazing-fcb-qualify-for-the-knockout-stages/ |title=Amazing: FCB qualify for the knockout stages |publisher=FC Basel |date=5 December 2017 |accessdate=28 August 2024}}</ref>

===Borussia Dortmund===
Akanji signed for [[Borussia Dortmund]] on 15 January 2018 during the winter transfer window for a reported fee of €18&nbsp;million<ref>{{Cite web |title=Wechsel perfekt! BVB bekommt Akanji sofort |trans-title=Transfer complete! BVB gets Akanji immediately |url=https://www.kicker.de/wechsel-perfekt-bvb-bekommt-akanji-sofort-714978/artikel |access-date=2026-03-14 |website=kicker |language=de-DE}}</ref> He signed a four-and-a-half-year contract dated until June 2022.<ref name="bvb 2018-01-15">{{cite web | last = Borussia Dortmund | year = 2018 | url = http://www.bvb.de/News/Uebersicht/BVB-verpflichtet-Schweizer-Nationalspieler-Manuel-Akanji | title = BVB verpflichtet Schweizer Nationalspieler Manuel Akanji| publisher=Borussia Dortmund | accessdate = 15 January 2018}}</ref><ref name="fcb 2018-01-15">{{cite web |last=FC Basel |year=2018 |url=https://www.fcb.ch/de-CH/News/2018/01/15/Manuel-Akanji-wechselt-zu-Borussia-Dortmund |title=Manuel Akanji wechselt zu Borussia Dortmund |publisher=FC Basel |accessdate=15 January 2018 |archive-date=3 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200303005956/https://www.fcb.ch/de-CH/News/2018/01/15/Manuel-Akanji-wechselt-zu-Borussia-Dortmund |url-status=dead |trans-title=Manuel Akanji is moving to Borussia Dortmund.}}</ref> On 2 February, Akanji made his BVB debut as an 87th minute substitute for [[André Schürrle]] in a 3–2 win at [[1. FC Köln]].<ref>{{cite web|url= https://www.dw.com/en/bundesliga-debut-double-for-michy-batshuayi-borussia-dortmund-do-just-enough/a-42433294|title= Bundesliga: Debut double for Batshuayi in BVB win|date=2 February 2018|access-date=14 November 2023|publisher=Deutsche Welle}}</ref>

On 27 September 2018, Akanji scored his first goal for the club and his first [[Bundesliga]] goal in a 7–0 victory over [[1. FC Nürnberg]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bundesliga.com/en/news/Bundesliga/borussia-dortmund-nuremberg-live-line-ups-stats-pulisic-reus-paco-alcacer-fantasy-512935.jsp|title=Marco Reus stars as breathtaking Borussia Dortmund put seven past Nuremberg|publisher=Bundesliga|accessdate=29 September 2018|archive-date=5 June 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190605050033/https://www.bundesliga.com/en/news/Bundesliga/borussia-dortmund-nuremberg-live-line-ups-stats-pulisic-reus-paco-alcacer-fantasy-512935.jsp|url-status=dead}}</ref> Akanji was widely criticised for his costly errors during Dortmund's failed challenge to [[FC Bayern Munich|Bayern Munich]] during the [[2019–20 Bundesliga|2019–20 season]]. Akanji was one of the main players singled out as a weak link in the team.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://bvbbuzz.com/2019/11/11/three-borussia-dortmund-players-need-improve/2/|title=Three Borussia Dortmund players who need to improve|date=11 November 2019|access-date=1 August 2020|archive-date=29 April 2021|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210429215427/https://bvbbuzz.com/2019/11/11/three-borussia-dortmund-players-need-improve/2/|url-status=dead}}</ref> Akanji played the full 90 minutes as Dortmund beat [[RB Leipzig]] 4–1 in the [[2021 DFB-Pokal Final]] at the [[Berlin Olympiastadion]] on 13 May 2021.<ref>{{cite web|url= https://www.bundesliga.com/en/bundesliga/news/rb-leipzig-borussia-dortmund-live-dfb-cup-final-line-ups-stats-haaland-sancho-15791|title= Jadon Sancho and Erling Haaland help Borussia Dortmund overpower RB Leipzig to win DFB Cup|access-date=14 November 2023|website=Bundesliga}}</ref>

===Manchester City===
====2022–23 season====
On 1 September 2022, Akanji joined [[Premier League]] champions [[Manchester City F.C.|Manchester City]], signing a contract until 2027<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.mancity.com/news/mens/city-sign-manuel-akanji-63797615 |title=City seal Akanji signing |website=ManCity.com |publisher=Manchester City |date=1 September 2022 |access-date=1 September 2022}}</ref> for a reported fee of £15&nbsp;million.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.skysports.com/football/news/11679/12685788/man-city-sign-defender-manuel-akanji-from-borussia-dortmund-for-15m|title=Man City sign defender Manuel Akanji from Borussia Dortmund for £15m|website=Sky Sports|date=1 September 2022}}</ref> He made his debut for City five days later, starting in a 4–0 away win over [[Sevilla FC|Sevilla]] in the [[2022–23 UEFA Champions League|Champions League]] group stage.<ref>{{cite web |last=Sutcliffe|first=Steve|url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/62800316 |title=Sevilla 0–4 Man City: Erling Haaland scores twice in comfortable Champions League opening win |work=[[BBC Sport]] |date=6 September 2022 |access-date=6 September 2022}}</ref>

He made his Premier League debut on 17 September, starting in a 3–0 away win over [[Wolverhampton Wanderers F.C.|Wolverhampton Wanderers]].<ref>{{cite web |last=Stone|first=Simon|url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/62859266 |title=Wolves 0–3 Manchester City: Erling Haaland scores again in dominant win |work=BBC Sport |date=6 September 2022 |access-date=6 September 2022}}</ref> He was voted the club's Player of the Month for October.<ref>{{Cite web |last=Clayton |first=David |title=Akanji voted Etihad Player of the Month for October |url=https://www.mancity.com/news/mens/manuel-akanji-named-etihad-player-of-the-month-for-october-63803074 |access-date=2022-11-18 |website=mancity.com |language=en}}</ref> On 17 May 2023, he scored his first goal for the club, which was also his first in the Champions League, with a header deflected by [[Éder Militão]] in a 4–0 home win over [[Real Madrid CF|Real Madrid]] in the semi-final second leg.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.uefa.com/uefachampionsleague/news/0281-18096cb89d5d-7ee3fd883927-1000--report-city-ease-past-holders-madrid/ |title=Man City 4–0 Real Madrid (agg: 5–1): Silva double helps City ease into Champions League final at holders' expense |publisher=UEFA |date=17 May 2023 }}</ref> During the [[2022–23 Premier League]], Akanji played more minutes than any other Manchester City defender.<ref>{{Cite web |last=Someoddpilot |first=Devs |date=1 June 2023 |title=Premier League Team of the Season: OptaJoe's XI |url=https://theanalyst.com/2023/06/premier-league-team-of-the-season-2022-23/ |access-date=2023-06-14 |website=The Analyst |language=en}}</ref>

====2023–24 season====
On 21 October 2023, Akanji received his first red card for Manchester City in a 2–1 win over [[Brighton & Hove Albion F.C.|Brighton & Hove Albion]] in the [[2023–24 Premier League|Premier League]].<ref>{{cite web|url= https://www.rte.ie/sport/soccer/2023/1021/1412197-akanji-sees-red-but-manchester-city-edge-past-brighton/|title= Akanji sees red but Manchester City edge past Brighton |date=21 October 2023|publisher=Raidió Teilifís Éireann}}</ref> On 25 October, he scored his first goal of [[2023–24 Manchester City F.C. season|the season]] in a 3–1 win over [[BSC Young Boys]] in the [[2023–24 UEFA Champions League|Champions League]].<ref>{{cite web|url= https://www.reuters.com/sports/soccer/haaland-brace-lifts-man-city-3-1-win-over-young-boys-champions-league-group-2023-10-25/|title= Haaland brace lifts Man City to 3–1 win over Young Boys|date=26 October 2023|website=Reuters}}</ref> He scored his first Premier League goal in a 6–1 win over [[A.F.C. Bournemouth|Bournemouth]] on 4 November<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.premierleague.com/news/3767738|title= Record-equalling Doku sends Man City top|date=4 November 2023|publisher=Premier League}}</ref> and, on 12 November, scored in a third consecutive match as City drew 4–4 with [[Chelsea F.C.|Chelsea]] at [[Stamford Bridge (stadium)|Stamford Bridge]].<ref>{{cite news|url= https://www.premierleague.com/news/3784029|title=Chelsea 4–4 Man City: Key stats from an instant classic|date=12 November 2023|publisher=Premier League}}</ref>

====2024–25 season====
On 10 August 2024, Akanji scored the winning penalty as Manchester City defeated [[Manchester United F.C.|Manchester United]] 7–6 on penalties to win the [[2024 FA Community Shield]] after a 1–1 draw in regular time.<ref>{{Cite news |last=Unwin |first=Will |date=2024-08-10 |title=Manchester City beat United on penalties to win Community Shield |url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/article/2024/aug/10/manchester-city-manchester-united-community-shield-match-report |access-date=2026-03-14 |work=The Guardian |language=en-GB |issn=0261-3077}}</ref>

====Loan to Inter Milan====
On 2 September 2025, Akanji joined [[Serie A]] side [[Inter Milan]] on a season-long loan.<ref>{{Cite web |last=Editorial |first=Man City |title=Akanji joins Inter on loan |url=https://www.mancity.com/news/mens/Akanji%20joins%20Inter%20on%20loan |access-date=2026-03-14 |website=Manchester City FC |language=en}}</ref>

==International career==
[[File:Manuel Akanji.jpg|thumb|upright|Akanji with [[Switzerland national football team|Switzerland]] at the [[2018 FIFA World Cup]]]]
Akanji made two appearances for the [[Switzerland national under-20 football team|Switzerland U-20 national team]]. His debut was on 7 September 2014 in the 0–0 draw against the [[Germany national under-20 football team|German U-20 national team]]. From 2014, he was a member of the [[Switzerland national under-21 football team|Switzerland U-21 team]] and made his debut for them on 26 March in the 0–3 defeat by the [[Italy national under-21 football team|Italian U-21 team]].{{citation needed|date=August 2022}} On 9 June 2017, Akanji made his debut for the [[Switzerland national football team|Swiss senior team]] in a 2–0 win against [[Faroe Islands national football team|Faroe Islands]] in a [[2018 FIFA World Cup qualification – UEFA Group B|2018 World Cup qualifying]] match, where he played the entire 90 minutes.<ref>{{Cite web |title=Färöer Inseln 0:2 Schweiz |url=https://www.football.ch/SFV/Nationalteams/A-Team/Statistik-und-Resultate.aspx/tg-2628390/ |access-date=2026-03-14 |website=www.football.ch}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |last=Thorgan |first=Hazard |date=2019-06-08 |title=7m cn |url=https://svizanasgrad.me/ |access-date=2026-03-14 |work=Svizanasgrad |language=en-GB}}</ref> He was included in Switzerland's 23-man squad for the [[2018 FIFA World Cup]] in Russia and started all four of the team's matches as they reached the [[2018 FIFA World Cup knockout stage#Round of 16|round of 16]].<ref>{{Cite web |title=Manuel Akanji: 10 things on Borussia Dortmund's Swiss international defender |url=https://www.bundesliga.com/en/bundesliga/news/manuel-akanji-10-things-on-borussia-dortmund-swiss-defender-8279 |access-date=2026-03-14 |website=www.bundesliga.com |language=en}}</ref> In May 2019, Akanji played in [[2019 UEFA Nations League Finals]], where his team finished fourth.<ref>{{Cite news |date=2019-06-08 |title=Nations League: England beat Switzerland 6-5 on penalties after 0-0 draw |url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/48191915 |access-date=2026-03-14 |work=BBC Sport |language=en-GB}}</ref>

In 2021, he was named in the Swiss squad for [[UEFA Euro 2020]].<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.football.ch/sfv/nationalteams/a-team/news/das-kader-des-schweizer-nationalteams-fuer-die-uefa-euro-ist-bekannt.aspx |title=Das Kader des Schweizer Nationalteams für die UEFA EURO ist bekannt |trans-title=The squad of the Swiss national team for the UEFA Euro is known |work=[[Swiss Football Association]] |date=31 May 2021 |access-date=31 May 2021 |language=de}}</ref> He started all five of Switzerland's matches as they reached the [[UEFA Euro 2020 knockout stage#Quarter-finals|quarter-finals]],<ref>{{cite web|url= https://www.bundesliga.com/en/bundesliga/news/manuel-akanji-who-is-the-borussia-dortmund-and-switzerland-defender-16380|title=Manuel Akanji: Who is the Borussia Dortmund and Switzerland defender hailed by Giorgio Chiellini?|access-date=14 November 2023|website=Bundesliga}}</ref> scoring his kick as the Swiss beat [[France national football team|France]] in a penalty shootout in the [[UEFA Euro 2020 knockout stage#Round of 16|round of 16]].<ref>{{Cite news |last=Murray |first=Scott |date=2021-06-28 |title=France 3-3 Switzerland (aet; pens 4-5): Euro 2020 last 16 – as it happened |url=http://www.theguardian.com/football/live/2021/jun/28/france-v-switzerland-euro-2020-last-16-score-updates-live |access-date=2026-03-14 |work=the Guardian |language=en-GB |issn=0261-3077}}</ref> However, in the quarter-final against [[Spain national football team|Spain]], he was one of three Swiss players to miss their spot kicks in the 4–2 penalty shootout loss.<ref>{{Cite news |date=2021-07-01 |title=Switzerland 1-1 Spain: Spain beat Switzerland on penalties to reach Euros semis |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/51198650 |access-date=2026-03-14 |work=BBC Sport |language=en-GB}}</ref>

On 24 September 2022, Akanji scored his first senior international goal against [[Spain national football team|Spain]] in a 2–1 [[2022–23 UEFA Nations League A|UEFA Nations League]] victory.<ref>{{cite web|title=Zwei Eckbälle für ein Halleluja: Nati überrascht in Spanien|url=https://www.srf.ch/sport/fussball/nationalmannschaft/nations-league-in-saragossa-zwei-eckbaelle-fuer-ein-halleluja-nati-ueberrascht-in-spanien|date=24 September 2022|access-date=24 September 2022|publisher=[[Schweizer Radio und Fernsehen|SRF]]|language=de-ch|trans-title=Two corner kicks for a Hallelujah: National team surprises in Spain}}</ref> Akanji was a member of the Swiss squad for the [[2022 FIFA World Cup]] and, on 7 December 2022, he scored the only goal for Switzerland in a 6–1 loss to [[Portugal national football team|Portugal]] in the [[2022 FIFA World Cup knockout stage#Round of 16|round of 16]].<ref>{{Cite web |title=Portugal vs. Switzerland – Football Match Summary – December 7, 2022 – ESPN |url=https://www.espn.com.sg/soccer/match/_/gameId/633842 |access-date=2022-12-07 |publisher=ESPN |language=en}}</ref>

On 7 June 2024, Akanji was named in Switzerland's squad for [[UEFA Euro 2024]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.reuters.com/sports/soccer/switzerland-announce-26-man-squad-euro-2024-2024-06-07/|title=Switzerland announce 26-man squad for Euro 2024|date=7 June 2024|website=Reuters|access-date=16 June 2024}}</ref> He played the full match in the team's opening [[UEFA Euro 2024 Group A|Group A]] fixture on 15 June, as the ''Nati'' defeated [[Hungary national football team|Hungary]] 3–1 in Cologne.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/live/cy99107knekt#Line-ups|title=Hungary 1–3 Switzerland LIVE: UEFA Euro 2024 – score, updates & reaction|website=BBC Sport|access-date=16 June 2024}}</ref> He helped Switzerland reach the quarter-finals for a second consecutive European Championship, where his team was eventually eliminated by [[England national football team|England]] on penalties. Akanji took the first spot kick for Switzerland in the [[Penalty shoot-out (association football)|shoot-out]], which [[Jordan Pickford]] saved, and with both teams scoring their remaining penalties, England advanced by winning 5–3.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/live/crgkevjm6zmt |title=England vs Switzerland LIVE: UEFA Euro 2024 football stream, score, report, prediction & updates |website=BBC Sport |date=6 July 2024 |accessdate=28 August 2024}}</ref> For his performances, Akanji was selected in the [[UEFA Euro 2024#Awards|Team of the Tournament]].<ref name="TOTT">{{cite news|url=https://www.uefa.com/euro2024/news/028f-1b61a0e91074-427664e9bbfe-1000--uefa-euro-2024-team-of-the-tournament/ |title=UEFA EURO 2024 Team of the Tournament |publisher=UEFA |date=16 July 2024 |access-date=16 July 2024}}</ref>

==Style of play==
Akanji is known for his cultured style of play, which is characterised by his technical ability, composure on the ball, and excellent passing range.<ref>{{Cite web |year=2019 |title=Manuel Akanji – Soccer Wiki: for the fans, by the fans |url=https://en.soccerwiki.org/player.php?pid=81113 |access-date=2023-09-22 |website=Soccer Wiki |language=en}}</ref><ref name=":0">{{Cite web |last=more |first=Sam Lee, Raphael Honigstein and |title=Manuel Akanji was available, experienced and looks a very good fit for Man City |url=https://www.nytimes.com/athletic/3550633/2022/08/31/manuel-akanji-man-city-transfer-tactics-profile/ |access-date=2023-09-22 |website=The Athletic |date=31 August 2022 |language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |last=Marshall |first=Tyrone |date=17 September 2022 |title=Akanji did four things to impress Guardiola on Man City Premier League debut |url=https://www.manchestereveningnews.co.uk/sport/football/man-city-wolves-news-akanji-25044500 |access-date=2023-09-22 |website=Manchester Evening News |language=en}}</ref> He is also a strong and physical [[Defender (association football)|defender]] who is comfortable in one-on-one situations and is adept at intercepting passes and making tackles.<ref name=":0" /><ref>{{Cite web |last=Odey |first=Emmanuel |date=29 April 2023 |title=Manuel Akanji: The Bargain of the Season? |url=https://bitterandblue.sbnation.com/2023/4/29/23703512/manuel-akanji-the-bargain-of-the-season |access-date=2023-09-22 |website=Bitter and Blue |language=en}}</ref><ref name=":1">{{Cite web |last=Desmond |first=Rhys |date=1 November 2022 |title=Manuel Akanji at Man City – Tactical Analysis |url=https://themastermindsite.com/2022/11/01/manuel-akanji-at-man-city-tactical-analysis/ |access-date=2023-09-22 |website=TheMastermindSite |language=en}}</ref><ref name=":2">{{Cite web |date=5 September 2022 |title=Manuel Akanji at Manchester City 2022/23 – scout report |url=https://totalfootballanalysis.com/player-analysis/manuel-akanji-at-man-city-202223-scout-report-tactical-analysis-tactics |access-date=2023-09-22 |website=Total Football Analysis Magazine |language=en-GB}}</ref>

His ability to read the game and make crucial interceptions as well as his calmness under pressure is well known among fans of the [[Premier League]]. Akanji's passing ability is also a key part of his game, and he is often involved in building attacks from the back.<ref name=":0" /><ref name=":1" /><ref name=":2" /><ref name=":3">{{Cite web |title=Manuel Akanji is Man City's bargain buy and now Pep Guardiola's intelligent problem-solver at right-back |url=https://www.skysports.com/football/news/11679/12716486/manuel-akanji-is-man-citys-bargain-buy-and-now-pep-guardiolas-intelligent-problem-solver-at-right-back |access-date=2023-09-22 |website=Sky Sports |language=en}}</ref> His long-range passing is particularly noteworthy, and he is capable of playing accurate diagonal balls to switch the play and create space for his teammates.<ref name=":0" /><ref name=":1" /><ref name=":3" /> Due to his passing abilities, Akanji has been deployed as both a [[left-back]] and [[right-back]], as well as occasionally a [[Libero (football)|libero]], much like teammate [[John Stones]], by [[Manchester City F.C.|City]] manager [[Pep Guardiola]].<ref name=":3" /><ref>{{Cite web |title=Manuel Akanji at left-back? Pep Guardiola's masterstroke against Arsenal turns the title race Man City's way |url=https://www.skysports.com/football/news/11095/12867335/manuel-akanji-at-left-back-pep-guardiolas-masterstroke-against-arsenal-turns-the-title-race-man-citys-way |access-date=2023-09-22 |website=Sky Sports |language=en}}</ref>

==Personal life==
Akanji was born in [[Neftenbach]],<ref name="munzinger"/> Switzerland, to a Swiss mother and a Nigerian father.<ref>{{Cite web|title=Manuel Akanji: 10 things on Borussia Dortmund's new Swiss international defender|url=https://www.bundesliga.com/en/news/Bundesliga/manuel-akanji-borussia-dortmund-defender-features-in-our-ten-things-profile-468262.jsp|access-date=30 October 2020|publisher=Bundesliga|archive-date=25 June 2023|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230625191839/https://www.bundesliga.com/en/news/Bundesliga/manuel-akanji-borussia-dortmund-defender-features-in-our-ten-things-profile-468262.jsp|url-status=dead}}</ref> His sister Sarah is a former footballer for FC Winterthur Frauen and a [[Social Democratic Party of Switzerland]] politician.<ref>{{cite web|url= https://www.blick.ch/politik/wegen-rassistischen-angriffen-sarah-akanji-zieht-sich-aus-politik-zurueck-id17876553.html|title= Sarah Akanji zieht sich aus Politik zurück|language=German|date=14 September 2022|access-date=14 November 2023|website=Blick|trans-title=Sarah Akanji withdraws from politics}}</ref>

In 2017, already a professional player, he completed his [[Vocational education#Switzerland|vocational training]] as a [[tradesman]] (″Kaufmann″). On Swiss TV in 2018 he showed excellent skills at [[mental calculation]].<ref>{{Cite news |title=Mathe-Genie Akanji: Netz steht nach TV-Auftritt Kopf |url=https://sport.sky.de/fussball/artikel/mathe-genie-akanji-netz-steht-nach-tv-auftritt-kopf/11553056/34372 |archive-url=http://web.archive.org/web/20250804194931/https://sport.sky.de/fussball/artikel/mathe-genie-akanji-netz-steht-nach-tv-auftritt-kopf/11553056/34372 |archive-date=2025-08-04 |access-date=2026-03-14 |work=Sky Sport |language=de-DE}}</ref><ref>{{Cite AV media |url=https://www.srf.ch/play/tv/sportpanorama/video/fussball-manuel-akanji-als-studiogast?urn=urn%3Asrf%3Avideo%3Af8cfc7ba-7ab4-481e-b34a-b7e16761cbd3 |title=Fussball: Manuel Akanji als Studiogast - Sportpanorama - Play SRF |access-date=2026-03-14 |via=www.srf.ch}}</ref>

